{
  "texts": [
    "The model may produce overly general explanations that fail to accurately address specific contradictions.",
    "For instance, if too many nonsensical concepts are provided simultaneously, the model might attempt to account for all of them without priority, diluting the explanation's focus and reducing its relevance to the main contradiction.In summary, by identifying nonsensical concepts and grounding relevant implicit knowledge from the concepts, the model receives more focused and relevant input.",
    "The clear performance boost from identifying one or two concepts highlights the superiority of our method in providing more accurate explanations.",
    "While additional concepts can help refine explanations, the performance of most models peaks at two nonsensical concepts, and even in cases where performance decreases with more concepts, it still remains better than when no nonsensical concepts are identified.",
    "Effect of few-shot examples in TIPFigure 5 depicts the impact of varying few-shot settings on the performance of Llama 2 models with different parameter sizes (7B, 13B and 70B) within the TIP framework."
  ]
}